WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.812 --> 00:00:07.770
MALE SPEAKER: OK, then.

00:00:07.770 --> 00:00:09.530
Now we today have the
honor or welcoming

00:00:09.530 --> 00:00:12.430
a man who knows more
about stories than anyone

00:00:12.430 --> 00:00:16.620
else I can think of and
who recently also chose

00:00:16.620 --> 00:00:18.120
to share his knowledge
in this book.

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:20.610
So it's a great opportunity.

00:00:20.610 --> 00:00:22.550
John Yorke is the
managing director

00:00:22.550 --> 00:00:24.950
of Company Pictures, the
UK drama independent,

00:00:24.950 --> 00:00:27.310
producing "Skins,"
"Shameless," "The White Queen,"

00:00:27.310 --> 00:00:28.640
and "Wolf Hall."

00:00:28.640 --> 00:00:30.890
For many years, he's been
responsible for a vast array

00:00:30.890 --> 00:00:34.730
of British drama, as both
head of Channel 4 drama

00:00:34.730 --> 00:00:37.880
and controller of
BBC drama production.

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:41.490
In 2005, he created the
BBC Writers Academy,

00:00:41.490 --> 00:00:43.860
a year-long in depth
training scheme which

00:00:43.860 --> 00:00:47.040
has produced a generation of
successful television writers.

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:49.690
He's also worked as
editor of "The Archers."

00:00:49.690 --> 00:00:52.840
He is currently a visiting
professor of English language

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:56.660
and literature at the University
of New Castle upon Tyne.

00:00:56.660 --> 00:01:00.190
So I would like for us all
to give a round of applause

00:01:00.190 --> 00:01:02.696
as a welcome to John Yorke.

00:01:02.696 --> 00:01:05.612
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:08.530 --> 00:01:10.980
JOHN YORKE: Thank you so much
for those generous words.

00:01:10.980 --> 00:01:13.370
I shall begin with a
thank you and apology.

00:01:13.370 --> 00:01:14.590
Firstly a thank you.

00:01:14.590 --> 00:01:17.470
I'm hugely flattered to be asked
to come and talk here today.

00:01:17.470 --> 00:01:19.962
It means something
very much to me.

00:01:19.962 --> 00:01:21.420
And second an
apology, because what

00:01:21.420 --> 00:01:23.560
I'm going to try and
do in the next 35,

00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:27.750
40 minutes is tell the
whole history and mechanics

00:01:27.750 --> 00:01:29.314
of how all
storytelling has worked

00:01:29.314 --> 00:01:30.480
since the beginning of time.

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:35.210
So if I rush through that
slightly, please forgive me.

00:01:35.210 --> 00:01:37.150
I'm going to take
loads of shortcuts,

00:01:37.150 --> 00:01:40.230
make loads of absurd
generalizations, loads

00:01:40.230 --> 00:01:42.090
of things where you may go, ahh.

00:01:42.090 --> 00:01:44.900
But if you feel like
going ahh, then please do.

00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:46.550
Please do stop me
and ask questions.

00:01:46.550 --> 00:01:47.450
It's absolutely fine.

00:01:47.450 --> 00:01:49.600
I'll try and leave
some time at the end.

00:01:49.600 --> 00:01:52.950
But in the interest of
brevity and moving on,

00:01:52.950 --> 00:01:55.240
what I'm going to
talk about today

00:01:55.240 --> 00:01:57.600
is what I'm going to
call story physics.

00:01:57.600 --> 00:01:59.980
I'm going to talk about
how the narrative works

00:01:59.980 --> 00:02:02.170
and explore the similarities
between narrative

00:02:02.170 --> 00:02:06.020
in film and television,
but also hopefully touch

00:02:06.020 --> 00:02:10.600
on theater, novel, and
narrative in life, about how

00:02:10.600 --> 00:02:12.310
we tell stories about
the institutions

00:02:12.310 --> 00:02:17.260
we work in, about our history,
and how perhaps, arguably, they

00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:19.675
all work in exactly
the same way.

00:02:19.675 --> 00:02:23.920
And perhaps that has something
to do with the laws of physics.

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:27.589
OK, so that's really what
I want to do in a nutshell.

00:02:27.589 --> 00:02:29.880
So I want to begin with a
quote from Andrew Stanton who

00:02:29.880 --> 00:02:32.800
worked for Pixar, and
some of maybe will know,

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:35.576
directed the film,
"Finding Nemo."

00:02:35.576 --> 00:02:38.004
And I came across this
quote some years ago.

00:02:38.004 --> 00:02:39.420
He said, "You often
hear the term,

00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:42.310
'You should have something
to say in a story,' but that

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:43.600
doesn't always mean a message.

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:45.810
It means truth, some
value that you yourself

00:02:45.810 --> 00:02:48.124
as a storyteller
believe in and then

00:02:48.124 --> 00:02:49.540
through the course
of the story be

00:02:49.540 --> 00:02:52.260
able to do the
debate that truth.

00:02:52.260 --> 00:02:54.120
Try to prove it wrong.

00:02:54.120 --> 00:02:56.020
Test it to its limits.

00:02:56.020 --> 00:02:59.190
This is the stuff I
really geek out on.

00:02:59.190 --> 00:03:01.980
I call this 'Story Physics."

00:03:01.980 --> 00:03:04.600
And story physics,
that whole subject

00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:07.280
of something confronted
by its opposite,

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:09.010
is really the heart
of what I want

00:03:09.010 --> 00:03:11.900
to talk about this afternoon.

00:03:11.900 --> 00:03:14.360
Now I want to begin
with a clip, if I may.

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:17.820
The first clip, it's from
"EastEnders," which some of you

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:22.910
may be familiar with, from about
20 years ago, which ages me.

00:03:22.910 --> 00:03:26.560
Because I was the script
editor on this very clip.

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:29.190
I suspect half of you probably
weren't even born or not

00:03:29.190 --> 00:03:31.180
